REs", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8199056386947632, "span": {"begin": 665, "end": 669}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR target genes", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7650735378265381, "span": {"begin": 707, "end": 722}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "prostate cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8683826923370361, "span": {"begin": 763, "end": 777}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8358579277992249, "span": {"begin": 887, "end": 892}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 959, "end": 961}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR variants", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9320014715194702, "span": {"begin": 984, "end": 995}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1111, "end": 1113}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "miRNA", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.7101571559906006, "span": {"begin": 1164, "end": 1169}}], "text": "The biological plausibility for this KER is considered high  The AR is a ligand-activated transcription factor part of the steroid hormone nuclear receptor family. Non-activated AR is found in the cytoplasm as a multiprotein complex with heat-shock proteins, immunophilins and, other chaperones (Roy et al. 2001). Upon activation through ligand binding, the AR dissociates from the protein complex, translocates to the nucleus and homodimerizes. Facilitated by co-regulators, AR can bind to DNA regions containing AREs and initiate transcription of target genes, that thus will be different in e.g. different tissues, life-stages, species etc.   Through mapping of AREs and ChIP sequencing studies, several AR target genes have been identified, mainly studied in prostate cells (Jin, Kim, and Yu 2013). Different co-regulators and ligands lead to altered expression of different sets of genes (Jin et al. 2013; Kanno et al. 2022). Alternative splicing of the AR can lead to different AR variants that also affects which genes are transcribed (Jin et al. 2013).  Apart from this canonical signaling pathway, the AR can suppress gene expression, indirectly regulate miRNA transcription, and have non-genomic effects by rapid activation of second messenger pathways in either presence or absence of a ligand (Jin et al. 2013).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:21:31 +0000 2026"}